   <TITLE>Fast Ehternet: 100BaseT</TITLE>
   <META NAME="Author" CONTENT="">
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../../gif/bg-slate.gif">

<P><B><FONT COLOR="#0080FF"><FONT SIZE=+3>100BASE-T Fast Ethernet</FONT></FONT></B></P>

<UL>
<P><IMG SRC="../../../gif/gr_diam.gif" HEIGHT=19 WIDTH=19><B><FONT COLOR="#000000"><FONT SIZE=+2>簡介</FONT></FONT></B></P>
</UL>

<UL>
<UL>
<LI>100BASE-T Fast Ethernet is an extension of the existing Ethernet IEEE
802.3<BR>
standard.</LI>

<LI>The new technology uses the existing 802.3 MAC layer, connected through
a <BR>
media-independent interface (MII) layer to one of three physical (PHY)
layers.<BR>
(See Figure 1.)</LI>

<LI>The minimum frame size remains 64 bytes. </LI>

<LI>The MII specification is similar to the 10 Mbps Ethernet attachment
unit interface<BR>
(AUI) and provides a single interface that can support external transceivers
for<BR>
any of the 100BASE-T media specifications.</LI>

<P><IMG SRC="fetfig2.gif" HEIGHT=295 WIDTH=540></P>

<UL>
<UL>
<P>Figure 1. <I>Compatible Ethernet and Fast Ethernet Architectures</I></P>
</UL>
</UL>
</UL>

<P><IMG SRC="../../../gif/gr_diam.gif" HEIGHT=19 WIDTH=19><B><FONT SIZE=+2>線材選擇</FONT></B></P>
</UL>

<UL>
<UL>
<P>100BASE-T supports three media specifications: 100BASE-TX, 100BASE-T4,
and <BR>
100BASE-FX. The 100BASE-T standard also defines a 100BASE-T repeater and
a<BR>
management interface. 100BASE-TX, 100BASE-T4, and 100BASE-FX systems can<BR>
be mixed together and interconnected through a hub.</P>

<UL>
<LI>100BASE-TX</LI>

<UL>
<LI>a two-pair system for data grade (EIA 568 Category 5) UTP and STP<BR>
cabling</LI>

<LI>based on FDDI/CDDI PMD specification.(4B/5B encoding)</LI>
</UL>

<LI>100BASE-T4 </LI>

<UL>
<LI>a four-pair system for both voice and data grade (Category 3, 4, or
5)<BR>
UTP cabling</LI>

<LI>three (1,3,4) of the four pairs are for frame transmission (33.3Mbps
<BR>
each, half- duplex). The second pair is for carrier sense. (8B6T encoding)
</LI>

<LI>to address the needs of the installed base of UTP C3 used in older<BR>
10BASE-T networks</LI>
</UL>

<LI>100BASE-FX</LI>

<UL>
<LI>a two-strand fiber system</LI>

<LI>for extended distances, downlinks, and backbones. (see Figure 2)</LI>
</UL>
</UL>
</UL>

<P><IMG SRC="../../../gif/gr_diam.gif" HEIGHT=19 WIDTH=19><B><FONT SIZE=+2>10/100 Mbps
自動判斷</FONT></B></P>

<UL>
<LI>To provide easy migration from 10 to 100 Mbps, the 100BASE-T standard
includes<BR>
automatic speed sensing as part of the Auto-Negotiation, or NWay, function.
</LI>

<LI>This allows an adapter or switch capable of transmitting at both 10BASE-T
and<BR>
100BASE-T speeds to automatically communicate available modes of operation.<BR>
(see Figure 3, the 10-100 switch.)</LI>
</UL>

<P><IMG SRC="../../../gif/gr_diam.gif" HEIGHT=19 WIDTH=19><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Topology
Rules</FONT></B></P>

<UL>
<LI>Fast Ethernet preserves the critical 100-meter maximum UTP cable length
from the <BR>
hub to the desktop. </LI>

<LI>100BASE-T networks will be broken up into multiple collision domains.
Each port<BR>
on a bridge, router, or switch starts another collision domain. </LI>

<LI>The 100BASE-T standard defines two classes of repeaters, called Class
I and Class<BR>
II repeaters. A collision domain can include at most one Class I or two
Class II repeaters. </LI>
</UL>

<P><IMG SRC="../../../gif/gr_diam.gif" HEIGHT=19 WIDTH=19><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Key topology
rules are as follows:</FONT></B></P>
</UL>

<UL>
<UL>
<LI>Using two Class II repeaters, the maximum diameter of the collision
domain is 205 <BR>
meters (typically 100m + 5m + 100m). (see level 2 in Figure 2)</LI>

<LI>With just a single Class II repeater in the collision domain, the diameter
can be extended<BR>
to 309 meters using fiber (typically 100m UTP + 209m fiber downlink). (level
3 in Figure 2)</LI>

<LI>With a single Class I repeater in the collision domain, the diameter
can be extended to 261<BR>
meters using fiber (typically 100m UTP + 161m fiber downlink). (not shown
in Figure 2)</LI>

<LI>Connecting from MAC to MAC (switch to switch, or end-station to switch)
using half-duplex<BR>
100BASE-FX, a 412-meter fiber run is allowed. (level 4 in Figure 2)</LI>

<LI>For very long distance runs, a nonstandard, full-duplex version of
100BASE-FX can be <BR>
used to connect two devices over a 2-kilometer distance. (level 1 in Figure
2)</LI>
</UL>
</UL>

<CENTER><P><IMG SRC="fetfig3.gif" HEIGHT=681 WIDTH=409></P></CENTER>

<CENTER><P>Figure 2. <I>100BASE-T Topology Rules</I></P></CENTER>

